Add tests for the remaining three methods in `GlobalExceptionHandler`: `IllegalArgumentException`, `TechnicalException`, and generic `Exception`.

```java
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertEquals;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertNotNull;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertTrue;

import java.lang.reflect.Method;
import java.util.Map;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.springframework.core.MethodParameter;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.web.bind.MissingRequestHeaderException;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestHeader;
import org.springframework.web.servlet.ModelAndView;

class GlobalExceptionHandlerTest {

    private final GlobalExceptionHandler handler =
            new GlobalExceptionHandler();

    @Test
    void shouldHandleMissingRequestHeaderException() throws Exception {
        Method method = GlobalExceptionHandlerTest.class
                .getDeclaredMethod("dummyEndpoint", String.class);

        MethodParameter methodParameter =
                new MethodParameter(method, 0);

        MissingRequestHeaderException exception =
                new MissingRequestHeaderException(
                        "APP_ID",
                        methodParameter
                );

        Map<String, String> response =
                handler.handleMissingRequestHeader(exception);

        assertNotNull(response);
        assertTrue(response.containsKey("message"));
        assertNotNull(response.get("message"));
        assertTrue(response.get("message").contains("APP_ID"));
    }

    @Test
    void shouldHandleIllegalArgumentException() {
        IllegalArgumentException exception =
                new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid APP_ID");

        ResponseEntity<Map<String, Object>> response =
                handler.handleIllegalArgumentException(exception);

        assertNotNull(response);
        assertEquals(400, response.getStatusCode().value());
        assertNotNull(response.getBody());
        assertEquals(
                "Invalid APP_ID",
                response.getBody().get("message")
        );
    }

    @Test
    void shouldRedirectToTechnicalErrorForTechnicalException() {
        TechnicalException exception =
                new TechnicalException("Technical failure");

        ModelAndView response =
                handler.handleGenericUiException(exception);

        assertNotNull(response);
        assertEquals(
                "redirect:/error/technical",
                response.getViewName()
        );
    }

    @Test
    void shouldRedirectToTechnicalErrorForGenericException() {
        ModelAndView response = handler.handleGeneric();

        assertNotNull(response);
        assertEquals(
                "redirect:/error/technical",
                response.getViewName()
        );
    }

    @SuppressWarnings("unused")
    private void dummyEndpoint(
            @RequestHeader("APP_ID") String appId
    ) {
        // Used only to construct MethodParameter in the test.
    }
}
```

One possible adjustment: your `TechnicalException` constructor may not accept a message. In that case, create it using the constructor available in your class, for example:

```java
TechnicalException exception = new TechnicalException();
```

or:

```java
TechnicalException exception =
        new TechnicalException(
                "Technical failure",
                new RuntimeException("Root cause")
        );
```

You can also simplify and strengthen the generic handler so the exception is logged:

```java
@ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
public ModelAndView handleGeneric(Exception exception) {
    log.error("Unhandled application error", exception);
    return new ModelAndView("redirect:/error/technical");
}
```

Then update the test call:

```java
ModelAndView response =
        handler.handleGeneric(
                new RuntimeException("Unexpected failure")
        );
```

This covers every method currently visible in the handler.
